dpoint of the line segment.</p><p>Between a <strong>midpoint M</strong> and=
 an endpoint, each segment has the same length. Section <strong>AB</strong>=
 is frequently claimed to be divided in half by point <strong>M</strong>.</=
p><div id=3D"AdThrive_Content_2_tablet" class=3D"adthrive-ad adthrive-conte=
nt adthrive-content-2 adthrive-ad-cls" style=3D"min-height: 250px;"></div><=
p>In other words, a line segment=E2=80=99s midpoint is its <strong>center</=
strong> or <strong>middle</strong>. The midway of every line segment is dif=
ferent.</p><p>Therefore, <strong>by applying the midpoint formula, we can d=
etermine the midpoint</strong> of any segment on the coordinate plane.</p><=
p>In <strong>2-Dimensional Space</strong> (2D) midpoint (or mean) is also k=
nown as the median and simplifies calculations because there are just two e=
ndpoints.</p><p>This &nbsp;<strong>Midpoint Calculator</strong> can locate =
the endpoint of a line segment by using the start-point and midpoint coordi=
nates since midpoints and endpoints are related words.</p><h2><span id=3D"H=
ow_To_Use_a_Midpoint_Calculator">How To Use a Midpoint Calculator</span></h=
2><p>You can use the <strong>Midpoint Calculator</strong> by following the =
instructions below.</p><h3><span id=3D"Step_1">Step 1</span></h3><p>Fill in=
 the provided input boxes with the given data points.</p><h3><span id=3D"St=
ep_2">Step 2</span></h3><p>Click&nbsp;on the&nbsp;<strong>=E2=80=9C</strong=
><strong>Submit</strong><strong>=E2=80=9C</strong>&nbsp;button to determine=
 the <strong>midpoint</strong> of the given data points and also the whole =
step-by-step solution for the midpoint calculation will be displayed.</p><h=
2><span id=3D"How_Does_the_Midpoint_Calculator_Work">How Does the Midpoint =
Calculator Work?</span></h2><p>The<strong> Midpoint calculator</strong> wor=
ks by using coordinates of two points A(xA, yA) and B(xB, yB) in the two-di=
mensional Cartesian coordinate plane and finding the halfway point between =
two given points A and B on a line segment.</p><p>It=E2=80=99s an online Ge=
ometry tool that requires 2 endpoints in the two-dimensional Cartesian coor=
dinate plane.</p><p>It=E2=80=99s an alternate method to finding the midpoin=
t of a line segment without a compass and ruler.</p><div id=3D"AdThrive_Con=
tent_3_tablet" class=3D"adthrive-ad adthrive-content adthrive-content-3 adt=
hrive-ad-cls" style=3D"min-height: 250px;"></div><ul><li>Label the coordina=
tes (x=E2=82=81,y=E2=82=81) and (x=E2=82=82,y=E2=82=82) and place the value=
s into the formula.</li><li>Add the obtained values in the parentheses and =
divide each value by 2.</li><li>The new values will form the new coordinate=
s of the midpoint.</li><li>Check the results using the midpoint calculator.=
</li></ul><p>If we have a line segment and want to cut that section into tw=
o equal parts,&nbsp;<span style=3D"letter-spacing: var( --e-global-typograp=
hy-fd4917d-letter-spacing ); word-spacing: var( --e-global-typography-fd491=
7d-word-spacing );">we will need to know the center. We can do this by find=
ing the midpoint that we can measure with a ruler or a formula that involve=
s the coordinates of each endpoint of the segment.</span></p><p>The midpoin=
t is the specific average of each coordinate of the section, forming a new =
coordinate point.</p><h3><span id=3D"Midpoint_Formula">Midpoint Formula</sp=
